WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:17.000
Oxford Bookworms Fact Files.
London.
by John Escott.
read by Judy Bennett.
published and copyright
Oxford University Press 2000.

00:30.000 --> 00:39.000
Chapter 1

00:39.000 --> 00:44.000
This is London.

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
Every year, more than 9 million people

00:48.000 --> 00:52.000
come from countries all over the world

00:52.000 --> 00:55.000
to visit London.

00:55.000 --> 01:00.000
They go to the theatres and museums.

01:00.000 --> 01:04.000
They look at interesting old buildings,

01:04.000 --> 01:08.000
many of them hundreds of years old.

01:08.000 --> 01:13.000
They sit or walk in the beautiful parks

01:13.000 --> 01:17.000
or have a drink in a pub.

01:17.000 --> 01:20.000
They go to Oxford Street

01:20.000 --> 01:25.000
and look at the shops or to Harrods.

01:25.000 --> 01:30.000
Two million visitors go to the Tower of London.

01:30.000 --> 01:37.000
A million more go to see St Paul's Cathedral.

01:37.000 --> 01:43.000
Yes, London is a big and beautiful city

01:43.000 --> 01:47.000
with lots to see and do.

01:47.000 --> 01:50.000
How did it all begin?

02:10.000 --> 02:12.000
Chapter 2

02:12.000 --> 02:15.000
In the Beginning

02:15.000 --> 02:19.000
The name London comes from the Romans.

02:19.000 --> 02:23.000
There were people living here before they came,

02:23.000 --> 02:28.000
but we do not know very much about them.

02:28.000 --> 02:33.000
The Romans came to England in AD 43.

02:33.000 --> 02:36.000
They built houses and other buildings

02:36.000 --> 02:40.000
and made a town next to the River Thames.

02:40.000 --> 02:44.000
They called the town Londonium.

02:45.000 --> 02:48.000
They built a bridge over the river

02:48.000 --> 02:53.000
and ships came up to Londonium from the sea.

02:53.000 --> 02:57.000
The town got bigger and bigger.

02:57.000 --> 03:01.000
Important new buildings went up

03:01.000 --> 03:05.000
and you can see some of the Roman city wall today

03:05.000 --> 03:09.000
near the Museum of London.

03:10.000 --> 03:16.000
It was a rich town with about 50,000 people living in it.

03:16.000 --> 03:20.000
But soon after AD 400,

03:20.000 --> 03:25.000
the Romans left Londonium to go back to Rome

03:25.000 --> 03:30.000
and nobody lived in the town for many hundreds of years.

03:30.000 --> 03:34.000
The buildings began to fall down.

03:34.000 --> 03:38.000
Danish soldiers destroyed more buildings

03:38.000 --> 03:42.000
nearly 500 years later.

03:42.000 --> 03:46.000
King Alfred was king of England then.

03:46.000 --> 03:49.000
He got the Danes to leave London

03:49.000 --> 03:54.000
and his men built the town again.

03:54.000 --> 03:56.000
In 1066,

03:56.000 --> 04:02.000
William the Conqueror came to England from France to be king.

04:02.000 --> 04:04.000
Soon after,

04:04.000 --> 04:09.000
he began to build the Tower of London.

04:09.000 --> 04:14.000
When Henry VIII was king in 1509,

04:14.000 --> 04:19.000
50,000 people lived in London again.

04:19.000 --> 04:22.000
By the year 1600,

04:22.000 --> 04:25.000
there were 200,000,

04:25.000 --> 04:31.000
but a lot of them lived in old and dirty buildings.

04:32.000 --> 04:35.000
In 1665,

04:35.000 --> 04:40.000
100,000 people died from an illness called the Plague.

04:40.000 --> 04:45.000
This was called the Year of the Great Plague.

04:45.000 --> 04:47.000
A year later,

04:47.000 --> 04:49.000
in 1666,

04:49.000 --> 04:52.000
there was a big fire,

04:52.000 --> 04:55.000
the fire of London.

04:55.000 --> 04:59.000
It began in a house in Pudding Lane,

04:59.000 --> 05:02.000
the London Bridge.

05:02.000 --> 05:05.000
More than a quarter of a million Londoners

05:05.000 --> 05:09.000
lost their homes in the fire.

05:09.000 --> 05:12.000
It destroyed St Paul's Cathedral

05:12.000 --> 05:16.000
and 88 other churches.

05:16.000 --> 05:21.000
But the fire also destroyed most of the worst old buildings,

05:21.000 --> 05:25.000
and the new houses that went up after this

05:25.000 --> 05:29.000
were better for people to live in.

05:29.000 --> 05:33.000
A new St Paul's Cathedral was built between

05:33.000 --> 05:38.000
1675 and 1711.

05:38.000 --> 05:40.000
By 1881,

05:40.000 --> 05:44.000
more than 3 million people lived in London.

05:44.000 --> 05:49.000
Today, more than 6 million people live here.

05:49.000 --> 05:53.000
There were 8 million in the 1960s,

05:53.000 --> 05:57.000
but in the 1970s and 1980s,

05:57.000 --> 06:01.000
people moved out of the centre of London.

06:01.000 --> 06:20.000
MUSIC

06:20.000 --> 06:22.000
Chapter 3

06:22.000 --> 06:25.000
Visiting the City

06:25.000 --> 06:28.000
A quick and easy way

06:28.000 --> 06:31.000
to get to different places in the city

06:31.000 --> 06:34.000
is to use an underground train.

06:34.000 --> 06:37.000
The trains run all day

06:37.000 --> 06:40.000
and most of the night.

06:40.000 --> 06:45.000
Buy your ticket before you get on the train.

06:45.000 --> 06:48.000
It's better not to make your journey

06:48.000 --> 06:53.000
between 8 o'clock and 10 o'clock in the morning

06:53.000 --> 06:58.000
or 4 o'clock and 6 o'clock in the evening.

06:58.000 --> 07:02.000
These are called the rush hours.

07:02.000 --> 07:05.000
Thousands of people are going to work

07:05.000 --> 07:08.000
or coming home again then,

07:08.000 --> 07:11.000
and it is difficult to move

07:11.000 --> 07:16.000
or to find a place to sit on the train.

07:16.000 --> 07:19.000
You can see much more of London

07:19.000 --> 07:23.000
from one of its famous red buses.

07:23.000 --> 07:27.000
Some special visitors' buses take you

07:27.000 --> 07:31.000
to many of the interesting places in the city

07:31.000 --> 07:33.000
on one journey.

07:33.000 --> 07:38.000
It takes about one and a half hours,

07:38.000 --> 07:42.000
but you can break your journey and get off

07:42.000 --> 07:48.000
and on again at the different places you want to visit.

07:49.000 --> 07:54.000
London taxis are called black cabs.

07:54.000 --> 07:57.000
Most of them are black,

07:57.000 --> 08:00.000
but some are not.

08:00.000 --> 08:07.000
You can stop one if it has a for hire sign on it.

08:07.000 --> 08:13.000
The drivers are usually friendly and helpful.

08:14.000 --> 08:19.000
Why not take a boat trip along the river Thames?

08:19.000 --> 08:26.000
Boats leave Westminster Pier and Charing Cross Pier,

08:26.000 --> 08:32.000
and they go to Tower Pier and Greenwich.

08:32.000 --> 08:35.000
Between April and October,

08:35.000 --> 08:40.000
you can take a longer boat trip to Hampton Court,

08:40.000 --> 08:42.000
about four hours,

08:42.000 --> 08:46.000
a beautiful palace in a big park.

08:46.000 --> 09:10.000
Chapter 4

09:10.000 --> 09:13.000
Some places to go.

09:13.000 --> 09:18.000
The Queen has her London home at Buckingham Palace.

09:18.000 --> 09:21.000
It is at the end of the Mall,

09:21.000 --> 09:26.000
a long road that begins at Trafalgar Square.

09:26.000 --> 09:30.000
At half past eleven most mornings,

09:30.000 --> 09:35.000
the soldiers at Buckingham Palace change the guard.

09:35.000 --> 09:38.000
It takes about thirty minutes,

09:38.000 --> 09:42.000
and hundreds of visitors come to watch.

09:42.000 --> 09:46.000
And in August and September,

09:46.000 --> 09:51.000
you can usually visit some of the rooms in the palace.

09:51.000 --> 09:55.000
But there are always lots of people coming to see them,

09:55.000 --> 09:59.000
so be ready to wait.

09:59.000 --> 10:05.000
You can also visit the Royal Muse at the palace.

10:05.000 --> 10:11.000
This is the home of the Queen's horses and coaches.

10:11.000 --> 10:15.000
The Queen's Gallery is also at the palace,

10:15.000 --> 10:20.000
and you can visit it at most times of the year.

10:20.000 --> 10:26.000
Here you can see pictures from all over the world.

10:26.000 --> 10:30.000
The Tower of London is now a museum,

10:30.000 --> 10:34.000
and one of London's most famous buildings.

10:34.000 --> 10:39.000
More than two million people visit it every year.

10:39.000 --> 10:44.000
Yeoman waters, also called beef eaters,

10:44.000 --> 10:49.000
tell them all about the tower.

10:49.000 --> 10:52.000
You can see the crown jewels,

10:52.000 --> 10:57.000
and visit the bloody tower and the white tower.

10:57.000 --> 11:00.000
Or take a walk round the wall,

11:00.000 --> 11:05.000
and perhaps see one of the tower's famous black birds,

11:05.000 --> 11:08.000
the ravens.

11:08.000 --> 11:12.000
Tower Bridge is near the Tower of London.

11:12.000 --> 11:17.000
It is one of the most famous bridges in the city,

11:17.000 --> 11:22.000
and first opened in 1894.

11:22.000 --> 11:29.000
St Paul's Cathedral is not far away on Ludget Hill.

11:29.000 --> 11:35.000
It was built by Sir Christopher Wren after the fire of London.

11:35.000 --> 11:41.000
Wren built more than 50 London churches.

11:41.000 --> 11:47.000
Visitors can go up to the Golden Gallery to look across London.

12:06.000 --> 12:11.000
Chapter 5 Westminster

12:11.000 --> 12:16.000
Westminster Abbey is more than 900 years old

12:16.000 --> 12:21.000
and is a very famous London church.

12:21.000 --> 12:24.000
After William the Conqueror,

12:24.000 --> 12:31.000
every king and queen of England was crowned king or queen here.

12:32.000 --> 12:37.000
The houses of Parliament are near Westminster Abbey.

12:37.000 --> 12:41.000
This is the home of the British government.

12:41.000 --> 12:48.000
The clock high up on the building is called Big Ben.

12:48.000 --> 12:52.000
The Prime Minister, the head of the British government,

12:52.000 --> 12:56.000
lives at 10 Downing Street.

12:56.000 --> 13:00.000
Walk along Parliament Street to Whitehall,

13:00.000 --> 13:03.000
past the government buildings,

13:03.000 --> 13:09.000
and you can see the little street on your left.

13:09.000 --> 13:13.000
Parks and Gardens

13:13.000 --> 13:17.000
When you are tired of looking at buildings,

13:17.000 --> 13:24.000
you can sit or walk in one of London's beautiful parks.

13:24.000 --> 13:29.000
Hyde Park has a lake in the middle called the Serpentine.

13:30.000 --> 13:34.000
And you can take a boat out on the water.

13:34.000 --> 13:42.000
It is a good place to get away from the crowds and the noise of the city.

13:42.000 --> 13:49.000
You can listen to the speakers at speakers corner near Marble Arch.

13:49.000 --> 13:54.000
People from all over the world come and speak here.

13:54.000 --> 13:59.000
You can ask a speaker some difficult questions if you like,

13:59.000 --> 14:06.000
or you can stand on a box and speak to some of the listeners.

14:06.000 --> 14:12.000
Kensington Gardens is next to Hyde Park.

14:12.000 --> 14:16.000
Here you can see the statue of Peter Pan,

14:16.000 --> 14:24.000
the famous boy in the children's story, Peter Pan, by J.M. Barrie.

14:24.000 --> 14:29.000
Regent's Park is the home of London Zoo.

14:29.000 --> 14:36.000
The zoo has thousands of birds and animals from all over the world.

14:36.000 --> 14:40.000
There is also a theatre in the park.

14:41.000 --> 14:45.000
On a summer's evening, you can sit out under the night sky

14:45.000 --> 14:49.000
and watch a play by William Shakespeare,

14:49.000 --> 14:53.000
England's most famous writer.

14:53.000 --> 14:57.000
St James's Park is next to the mall.

14:57.000 --> 15:03.000
It is smaller, but many people think it is more beautiful.

15:10.000 --> 15:24.000
Chapter 6

15:24.000 --> 15:29.000
Shops and Eating

15:29.000 --> 15:32.000
The most famous shop in London,

15:32.000 --> 15:36.000
some people say the most famous in the world,

15:36.000 --> 15:39.000
is Harrods in Knightsbridge.

15:39.000 --> 15:44.000
It opened in 1849.

15:44.000 --> 15:47.000
Oxford Street has many big shops,

15:47.000 --> 15:49.000
Selfridges,

15:49.000 --> 15:52.000
Marks and Spencer,

15:52.000 --> 15:54.000
John Lewis,

15:54.000 --> 15:57.000
Debenhams.

15:57.000 --> 16:02.000
There are always lots of people looking at the shops here,

16:02.000 --> 16:08.000
but at Christmas, thousands more people come to see the wonderful Christmas lights.

16:08.000 --> 16:14.000
And to buy things for their friends and family for Christmas.

16:14.000 --> 16:19.000
Charing Cross is famous for its book shops.

16:19.000 --> 16:25.000
There are lots of them, and they sell old and new books.

16:25.000 --> 16:31.000
One of the oldest and most famous is foils.

16:31.000 --> 16:34.000
It has thousands of books,

16:34.000 --> 16:42.000
but it can sometimes be very difficult to find the book you want.

16:42.000 --> 16:46.000
Covent Garden was once a big food market,

16:46.000 --> 16:51.000
but now it has lots of small shops and cafes,

16:51.000 --> 16:56.000
and there are street performers to watch.

16:56.000 --> 17:00.000
There are two very famous markets in London,

17:00.000 --> 17:04.000
Petticoat Lane Market, open on Sundays,

17:04.000 --> 17:07.000
is in Middlesex Street,

17:07.000 --> 17:14.000
and is a good place to buy cheap clothes and things for the home.

17:14.000 --> 17:19.000
At the market in Portobello Road, open on Saturdays,

17:19.000 --> 17:22.000
you can buy old clocks,

17:22.000 --> 17:29.000
old chairs and tables and hundreds of other things.

17:29.000 --> 17:35.000
You can find food from nearly every country in the world in London,

17:35.000 --> 17:39.000
in Soho, in the West End of London,

17:39.000 --> 17:44.000
C-Map on pages 18 and 19.

17:44.000 --> 17:50.000
You can eat food from Italy, India, China,

17:50.000 --> 17:56.000
Japan, Greece and lots more places.

17:56.000 --> 18:01.000
There are also thousands of pubs in the city.

18:01.000 --> 18:06.000
In many pubs, you can eat as well as drink.

18:06.000 --> 18:10.000
Or why not have some English fish and chips?

18:10.000 --> 18:14.000
They are cheap and good to eat.

18:14.000 --> 18:18.000
Or you can have tea at the rits in Piccadilly,

18:18.000 --> 18:22.000
or at the Savoy Hotel in the Strand.

18:26.000 --> 18:44.000
CHAPTER VII.

18:44.000 --> 18:47.000
GOING OUT.

18:47.000 --> 18:50.000
THEATERS AND MUSIC.

18:51.000 --> 18:56.000
London's West End has some of the best theatres in the world,

18:56.000 --> 19:00.000
so tickets can be expensive.

19:00.000 --> 19:04.000
Go in the afternoon, it is often cheaper.

19:04.000 --> 19:07.000
There is something for everybody.

19:07.000 --> 19:13.000
From a play by the Royal Shakespeare Company at the Barbican Theatre

19:13.000 --> 19:16.000
to Agatha Christie's The Mouse Trap,

19:16.000 --> 19:19.000
this play began in 1952,

19:19.000 --> 19:24.000
and thousands of visitors see it every year.

19:24.000 --> 19:27.000
There are lots of cinemas to visit.

19:27.000 --> 19:31.000
The most expensive are in the West End,

19:31.000 --> 19:36.000
but you can sometimes get cheap tickets on Mondays.

19:36.000 --> 19:41.000
You can hear wonderful music and singing from all over the world

19:41.000 --> 19:45.000
at the Royal Opera House in Covent Garden,

19:45.000 --> 19:49.000
the Royal Albert Hall in Kensington Gore,

19:49.000 --> 19:53.000
the London Coliseum in St Martin's Lane,

19:53.000 --> 19:57.000
and the Barbican Centre Silk Street.

19:57.000 --> 20:03.000
For ballet, go to the Sadler's Wells Theatre in Rosebury Avenue

20:03.000 --> 20:07.000
or to the Royal Opera House.

20:07.000 --> 20:14.000
To get cheap tickets by them an hour or two before it begins.

20:14.000 --> 20:18.000
Do you like to listen to jazz musicians?

20:18.000 --> 20:24.000
You can hear some of the best at Ronnie Scott's Club in Frith Street,

20:24.000 --> 20:29.000
or at the Bull's Head Barns at Barns Bridge,

20:29.000 --> 20:36.000
or at 100 Club at 100 Oxford Street.

20:36.000 --> 20:39.000
Sport.

20:39.000 --> 20:44.000
Some of the most famous English football clubs are in London.

20:44.000 --> 20:48.000
You can see Arsenal Play at Arsenal Stadium,

20:48.000 --> 20:52.000
Avernal Road, N5,

20:52.000 --> 20:56.000
Chelsea Play at Stamford Bridge,

20:56.000 --> 21:00.000
Fulham Road, SW6,

21:00.000 --> 21:05.000
and Tottenham Hotspur Play at White Heart Lane,

21:05.000 --> 21:09.000
High Road, N17.

21:09.000 --> 21:13.000
To watch the very English game of cricket,

21:13.000 --> 21:16.000
go to Lord's Cricket Ground,

21:16.000 --> 21:21.000
in St John's Wood, NWA.

21:21.000 --> 21:26.000
This is the home of cricket for most English people.

21:35.000 --> 21:46.000
CHAPTER 8

21:46.000 --> 21:51.000
Museums and Galleries

21:51.000 --> 21:54.000
The British Museum in Great Russell Street

21:54.000 --> 21:57.000
is the biggest museum in Britain.

21:57.000 --> 22:00.000
Tickets are free.

22:00.000 --> 22:05.000
The Museum of London, at 150 London Wall,

22:05.000 --> 22:09.000
is one of the most interesting museums in the city.

22:09.000 --> 22:14.000
It tells the story of London and its people.

22:14.000 --> 22:17.000
One more museum that tells a story

22:17.000 --> 22:22.000
is the Museum of the Moving Image, Momi,

22:22.000 --> 22:27.000
on the South Bank, under Waterloo Bridge.

22:27.000 --> 22:30.000
This tells the story of cinema and television,

22:30.000 --> 22:35.000
and there are many things for visitors to see and do.

22:35.000 --> 22:39.000
You can act with actors on a film set,

22:39.000 --> 22:44.000
or you can read the news on TV.

22:44.000 --> 22:47.000
Four million people visit the National Gallery

22:47.000 --> 22:50.000
in Trafalgar Square every year.

22:50.000 --> 22:54.000
They come to look at more than 2,000 pictures.

22:54.000 --> 22:57.000
Tickets are free.

22:57.000 --> 23:01.000
At the National Portrait Gallery in St Martin's Place,

23:01.000 --> 23:04.000
you can see pictures of famous people.

23:04.000 --> 23:08.000
Tickets are free here, too.

23:08.000 --> 23:14.000
The London Dungeon in Thule Street is a Museum of Horror.

23:14.000 --> 23:18.000
Half a million people visit it every year,

23:18.000 --> 23:23.000
but they don't always stay to see it all.

23:24.000 --> 23:27.000
Madame Tussauds in Marlabin Road

23:27.000 --> 23:31.000
is famous for its people made from wax.

23:31.000 --> 23:34.000
You can see famous people from the past

23:34.000 --> 23:37.000
and famous people of today,

23:37.000 --> 23:39.000
Abraham Lincoln,

23:39.000 --> 23:41.000
Mahatma Gandhi,

23:41.000 --> 23:43.000
Nelson Mandela,

23:43.000 --> 23:45.000
Pavarotti,

23:45.000 --> 23:48.000
Marilyn Monroe,

23:48.000 --> 23:50.000
Charlie Chaplin,

23:50.000 --> 23:53.000
Sylvester Stallone,

23:53.000 --> 23:56.000
and in the Chamber of Horrors,

23:56.000 --> 24:00.000
you can see some very bad people.

24:20.000 --> 24:22.000
Chapter 9.

24:22.000 --> 24:25.000
Places and parades.

24:25.000 --> 24:28.000
The City.

24:28.000 --> 24:32.000
Londoners often talk about the city.

24:32.000 --> 24:37.000
C-Map on pages 18 and 19.

24:37.000 --> 24:41.000
They are talking about the oldest part of London,

24:41.000 --> 24:44.000
the home of the Bank of England,

24:44.000 --> 24:48.000
and many other big offices.

24:48.000 --> 24:52.000
About 5,000 people live in the city,

24:52.000 --> 24:56.000
and at weekends it feels empty.

24:56.000 --> 24:59.000
But between Monday and Friday,

24:59.000 --> 25:02.000
nearly half a million people come here

25:02.000 --> 25:05.000
to work in the banks and offices.

25:05.000 --> 25:08.000
Look for the city men,

25:08.000 --> 25:12.000
with their dark suits and umbrellas.

25:12.000 --> 25:17.000
St Paul's Cathedral is in the middle of the city,

25:17.000 --> 25:21.000
and the Bank of England has an interesting museum

25:21.000 --> 25:23.000
that you can visit.

25:23.000 --> 25:28.000
Also in the city is a very tall building,

25:28.000 --> 25:31.000
60.6 metres high,

25:31.000 --> 25:34.000
called the Monument.

25:34.000 --> 25:37.000
Christopher Wren built this too,

25:37.000 --> 25:42.000
and it stands on the place where the fire of London began

25:42.000 --> 25:45.000
in 1666.

25:46.000 --> 25:51.000
Some interesting and exciting days.

25:51.000 --> 25:56.000
Every year, on a Saturday morning in June,

25:56.000 --> 26:00.000
foot guards and horse guards

26:00.000 --> 26:03.000
have a parade for the Queen.

26:03.000 --> 26:07.000
This is called Trooping the Colour.

26:07.000 --> 26:12.000
The colour is the flag that the soldiers carry.

26:12.000 --> 26:15.000
Thousands of people stand in the mall

26:15.000 --> 26:20.000
to see the Queen and the soldiers go past.

26:20.000 --> 26:24.000
The exciting Notting Hill Carnival

26:24.000 --> 26:28.000
is on the last Sunday and Monday in August.

26:28.000 --> 26:32.000
There are two wonderful parades to watch,

26:32.000 --> 26:37.000
one on Sunday and one on Monday.

26:37.000 --> 26:40.000
And you can see them going through the streets

26:40.000 --> 26:46.000
near Portobello Road and Ladbrook Grove.

26:46.000 --> 26:50.000
On the second Saturday in November,

26:50.000 --> 26:53.000
Londoners can see their new Lord Mayor

26:53.000 --> 26:56.000
in the Lord Mayor's show.

26:56.000 --> 26:59.000
A parade from Manchin House,

26:59.000 --> 27:03.000
the Lord Mayor's home, to the Strand.

27:03.000 --> 27:07.000
The Lord Mayor is the most important person

27:07.000 --> 27:10.000
in the city after the Queen.

27:10.000 --> 27:17.000
The first Mayor of London was Henry Fitzallen in 1189.

27:17.000 --> 27:20.000
They were not called Lord Mayor's

27:20.000 --> 27:24.000
until the time of King Henry VIII.

27:24.000 --> 27:27.000
Big red buses,

27:27.000 --> 27:29.000
London policemen,

27:29.000 --> 27:32.000
Buckingham Palace,

27:32.000 --> 27:34.000
Speakers Corner,

27:34.000 --> 27:36.000
Big Ben,

27:36.000 --> 27:39.000
Notting Hill Carnival.

27:39.000 --> 27:44.000
These are some of the things you can find in London.

27:44.000 --> 27:47.000
But there are many, many more.

27:47.000 --> 27:49.000
Come and see.

28:06.000 --> 28:09.000
Thank you.

